@mar 2

pomo sci fi

uses style and lang of hard science bt not as concerned w/accuracy
technophile-relation to science is more thru gadgedts
esp. interested in creating a particular feel in terms of the env (often dark)
given to using particular self-referential jargon that can be exclusionary (in the sense that it is helpful for the reader if they have read other books that have contributed to developing the genre)
often set in near-future on earth
the world is a hostile place!

Stock chars, lack of femininity.

@mar 4

Politics:
  80s punk & counter-culture
  cultish/exclusionary
  Built on a contemporary sense (beg. 80s) that the nexus/web of politics/economics/social org is so *vast* and *complex* that it is impossible to identify the origins of power
  Rebellion

Characters
  associated with rebellion
    trying to break out of this system
    manifests itself in crime and illegal things
  very male (male 'anti-hero')
  young alienated disoriented
    young = hip, alienated - post modern concern with fragmentation, the individual, chars need to be alienated and disconnected, you are a small cog in a much much larger machine
  morally numb, paranoid, into drugs
    most of the chars have some sort of dependency
    creates a natural sort of paranoid, besides coming out of this system of power - your choices are beyond you, there is a larger shadowy thing controlling your fate, forces them into a sort of moral numbness, you have to make these choices in order to survive and get on.


Setting
  Near Future
    when it first came out, much harder to envision, tho today much closer to reality
  Street level
  Filled with cast offs
  underground market
    outlaw zones, places where exchange of tech & data can go on freely and that these places are ihghly illegal
  internal world of virtual reality and cyberspace
    a lot of early sci fi is concerned with outerspace, where the cyberpunk is more concerned with the internal, whats inside our heads

Style/Aesthetic
  hard boiled detective novel
  western pulps (esp. anti hero or loner)
  horror genre
  urban, hip, gritty
    lots and lots of jargon
  narrative is non linear, disorienting, fragmented
    cyrber punk as a whole, is almost a necessity to play with the psychology of the mind, we never work linearly, we're a constantly looping construct
  high tech

The million dollar question:
  Are personality and identity constructed? how does each relate to agency/free will
  
# liberal arts seems full of people who take themselves too seriously, which for a techie, it's hard to not be taken back by their approach because *I* deal with the objective everyday, and I'm rewarded directly with being RIGHT or WRONG all the time and I can tell you a thing or two about that. 

