What to do about the question of wintermute
  completely controls armitage like a puppet

Most corporations in the text don't trade in goods and services but rather in information and data. How does this focus on abstracted (non-object) commodities change the power dynamics in the society of Neuromancer?

Who holds power in this novel? How?
  The gatekeepers of information


People/Environment as Data
  Linda Lee: her features reduced to a code
  environment as data possible to see Ninsei as a field of data, the way the matrix had once reminded him of proteins
  Dixie Flatline whose body has died but whose self lives on as a construct, a recorded memory in a computer that is capable of action, intention, real time memory
  McLuhan notion of global village almost literally realized.

  What kind of parallels does this have in contemporary society? What does this do to identity in the novel?

Women and femininity
  Molly has been called the 'embodiment of cyberpunk consciousness'

  What role does she play?
    She's the guide for Case and the reader. A narrative device that allows Gibson to explain a lot of the mechanics of the world. You can have Molly explain it to case.
    She's also a 'street samurai'

  Is this a traditional female role?
    Obv. not. Subverting a lot of traditional expectations of female chars, strong, intelligent, use her sexuality for her own benefit. Molly is literally a cyborg with all sorts of weird implants. She holds a position of power within a very male dominated society, she is the person that 'kills things'.

  How are procreation and technology related in the work?
    They clone them.
    cuts out the maternal, the ability to care for humans.


The Importance of Space
  Space an the navigation of space is v important in Neuromancer. This navigation takes place both on a virtual and on a real level. Cyberspace would seem to be the most important space - in conceptual terms and in terms of where the really important action takes place, but there are otehr very important spaces

  55, 59, 61, 64, 81, 82, 105, 116-121 - descriptions of cyberspace

