Equivalencies
  a set of equivalencies is established in this story, which both echoes the other cyberpunk works, and establishes its own unique set of relations. here the equivalences break down in the following manner
  body = computer = commodity = objectification

  does thi apply to our current society? can you think of any examples?

"A naked woman sitting at a computer, which attracts you most?"
  what is important/interesting about this quote?
    sex because it can be replicated, become almost solely for reproduction
  how is the female body treated in this text compared to the other text in the class?
    treated as 'meat'.
    naked woman is unaware of her body s a sexual object
    more as a function than a person
  
  Narrator establishes active relation to the reader (speaks directly to the reader). With this question, which attracts you most? the narrator implicates the reader as a desiring subject

  max is revelaed to be more attracted by the computer. in this sense, the computer diplaces the female body as the obj of desire, but at the same time by metonymic association the obj of desire is feminized.

  "I've got the option on your bioware"
    he's literally saying i have ownership over this body, human? def not mechanical. An interesting conflation b/w bio (body) and ware as in object

    "it's like i told you last night. From now on, if you want it, you pay. Just like everyone else."
      "unpacking the phrases". the word pay is heavily loaded, turning things into a commodity, just like everyone else. Implicates us as a reader, but again weeds out this sort of preferential treatment, est. angel as a capitalist. idea of micropolitics, use the system against itself.

    what are angel's structures of obsession?
      manipulation through sex, tired of being able to be manipulated and its power dynamics.

    how do these structures tie in her personal morals? do they at all?
      subtle sort of revenge at the start of the story, but gives them the option of escaping, some guilt of hers.

    she builds a machine to replace sexual intimacy between people. her alienated relation to sex leads her to view sex in an objectified manner, specifically, according to the language of technology; she views orgasms in terms of binary code, therefore programmable. so again we have language of technology to describe the biological

    she designs it, not for profit, but to ty to prove to herself that people would rather be intimate with one another

  What does Angel achieve at the end of the story? Revenge? Confirmation of her cynicism? Does she get what she wants?
    revenge and confirmation
      how?
	a personal attack on these two people.

  Is she guilty of anything at the end of the story?

@apr8

  The stated goal of Linden Lab is to create a world like the Metaverse described by Stephenson, a user defined world in which people can interact, play, do business, and otherwise communicate.
  while 2nd life is sometimes referred to as a game, this description does not fir the standard definition. it does not have points, scores, winners or losers, levels, an end strategy or most of the other characteristics.

Metaverse
  a fp inhabitation of virtual world where a person can be constantly connected 

Residents retain intellectual property rights in their digital creations, they can buy, sell and trade with other residents
second life has its own economy an currency referred to as Linden Dollars, current supports millions of US dollars. this commerce is handled in their own dollars.

fear of external influence

how does it compare?

bodily avatars in the metaverse
  no bodily needs
  exploration
  communication
  subcultures and events


